def add_features(df):
    df['year'] = df.index.year # yr exists already
    df['month'] = df.index.month
    df['day'] = df.index.day
    df['dayofweek'] = df.index.dayofweek

Data cleaning¶

Categorical variables¶

Perform one hot encoding on categorical variables. Machine learning algorithms assume (and require) the data to be numeric, so the categorical data must be pre-processed as a numerical data. Categorical variables turn into binary features that are 'one hot' encoded, so if a feature is represented by that column, it receives a 1, otherwise a 0.

  • The 'season' feature has 1: winter, 2: spring, 3: summer, 4: fall.
  • The 'holiday' and 'workingday' features are boolean: 1 when it is a holiday. 1 when it is a working day.

Numerical variables¶

Machine learning is sensitive to the relative scales of numerical variables. The range of all variables need to be normalized so that each feature contributes approximately proportionately to the calculation.

# Calculate based on UCI info to retrieve the actual temperature and weather information
#temp : Normalized temperature in Celsius. The values are divided to 41 (max)
#atemp: Normalized feeling temperature in Celsius. The values are divided to 50 (max)
#hum: Normalized humidity. The values are divided to 100 (max)
#windspeed: Normalized wind speed. The values are divided to 67 (max)
inversed_origin = pd.concat([inversed_df.iloc[:,0] * 41, #temperature
           inversed_df.iloc[:,1] * 50,                   #feeling temperature
           inversed_df.iloc[:,2] * 100,                  #humidity
           inversed_df.iloc[:,3] * 67],                  #wind speed
          axis=1)

Global explanation (overall)¶

SHAP Summary Plot¶

The SHAP values for XGBoost explain the margin output of the model, which explains the bike rental model.

This summary plot shows which features are most significant, and their range of effects over the dataset. It also reveals the positive and negative relationships of the predictors with the target variable in descending order. The top variables contribute more to the model than the bottom and thus exhibit high predictive power. The color shows how changes in the value of a feature affect the change of the target, which here are the counts of renting a bike.

  • y-axis: Variable name, in the order of importance from top to bottom.
  • x-axis: SHAP value, indicates the impact of each feature on renting a bike (above zero shows positive, otherwise negative). It shows whether the effect of that value is associated with a higher or lower prediction.
  • Gradient color: Value for the variable. In boolean, it will take two colors (e.g., year), but in numbers, it can contain the whole colormap spectrum.
  • Each point: a row from the original dataset.
In [63]:
#shap.summary_plot(shap_values) OR shap.plots.beeswarm(shap_values)
shap.summary_plot(shap_values, Xdf, feature_names=NAMES, max_display=7) #plot_type="bar" for bar type
  • People rented fewer bikes in 2011 but opposite in 2012.
    • Year 2011 is negatively correlated with the target variable, with lesser customers renting a bike.
  • People rented more bikes if feeling temperature and temperature are higher.
    • Temperature is positively correlated with the target variable, with more customers renting a bike.

SHAP Dependence Plot¶

While a SHAP summary plot provides a general overview of each feature, a SHAP dependence plot shows how the model output varies by feauture value. Note that every dot is a datapoint (e.g., each day), and the vertical dispersion at a single feature value results from interaction effects in the model.

If interaction_index=None, the dependence plot only shows a single feature. Otherwise, the feature used for coloring is automatically chosen to highlight what might be driving these interactions. Later we will see how to check that the interaction is really in the model with SHAP interaction values. Note that the row of a SHAP summary plot results from projecting the points of a SHAP dependence plot onto the y-axis, then recoloring by the feature itself.

In [64]:
# Use the dependence plot
# The shap_values[0] are explanations with respect to the negative class, while shap_values[1] are explanations with respect to the positive class
# X_original to view the original numerical data
# Can turn off interaction coloring with "interaction_index=None"
shap.dependence_plot("temp", shap_values, X_original, feature_names=NAMES, show=False) # interaction_index=None
plt.title("Relationship of temperature and feeling temperature");
  • Lower temperature shows a big decrease in shap values indicating lower rental counts.
  • At a certain point, the rental decreases when temperature grows.
